=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

For each long-haul tradegood,

	Choose two cities (source, consumer) at least 15 provinces apart
	Choose n=0-1 cities near to producer
	Choose m=0-1 cities near to consumer

	Set qty = 100 + (n-1)*25

		Each source city sells qty/n +- 10%
		Each consumer city buys qty/m +- 10%

	set distance = los(source, consumer)
	set profit = (125.5 + distance) * distance
	set premium = profit/qty

	set source city's cost at base price for item (base price is abitrary)
	set consumer city's cost at base+premium
	set prices for other source cities 1-5% lower
	set prices for other consumer cities 1-5% higher


try land routes within large regions first
	land routes must be at least 20-25 provinces

For each long-haul tradegood,
    Choose two regions, one to produce the good, and one to consume it.
    Within producer region, pick n=[1-3] cities to sell the item.
    Within consumer region, pick m=[1-3] cities to buy the item.

    Set qty = 100 + (n-1)*25

        Each source city sells qty/n +- 10%
        Each consumer city buys qty/m +- 10%

    Choose a source and consumer city.

    set distance = los(source, consumer)
    Set profit = (125.5 + distance) * distance
    Set premium = profit/qty

    Set source city's cost at base price for item
    Set consumer city's cost at base+premium
    Set prices for other source cities slightly lower ( < 5% deviation).
    Set prices for other consumer cities slightly higher ( < 5% deviation).


alternatively:

	pick two clusters of between 1-3 cities at least 10 (15?) provinces
	apart.  may either be separated by land or ocean.

	could be a separate routine to look for long-haul land routes


Notes:

	Cities chosen within regions should be close together, especially
	if the region is large.

	Quantity available to trade increases a bit if multiple cities sell.

	Longer trade routes are a bit more profitable per unit of distance
	than shorter ones.

	Ideally there would be enough unique long-haul tradegoods so that
	each region could produce one or two of them.  So far I've only
	thought of eight long-haul tradegoods.

	By fixing qty, we make lighter tradegoods naturally better than
	than heavier ones.


